"Abstract The Government's new draft Freedom of Information Bill, published on 24 May 1999 has been greeted by widespread criticism and demand for amendment. The draft Bill had been eagerly anticipated following the radical and much acclaimed White Paper (CM 3818) issued in December 1997, advancing the Government's proposals for a Freedom of Information Act. However, the draft Bill has delivered an empty promise of “Access to Information held by Public Authorities”, fettered by no less than 22 exemptions and couched in qualification, complexity and ambiguity. It is hardly surprising, then, that it has been generally condemned by civil rights groups. What the Government might not have anticipated when framing the draft Bill has been the hostile response of the business community, which has lent its weight to the growing controversy surrounding the draft Bill. David Lander analyses the draft proposals and considers what might be done to improve the Bill."
